
[1]precipice

   PREC'IPICE, n. [L. proecipitium, from proeceps,headlong; proe,
   forward,and ceps, for caput, head. See Chief.]

   1. Strictly, a falling headlong; hence, a steep descent of land; a fall
   or descent of land, perpendicular or nearly so.

   Where wealth, like fruit, on precipices grew.

   2. A steep descent, in general.

   In the breaking of the waves there is ever a precipice.

   Swift down the precipice of time it goes.
